35
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:41,000
I'll just go over it with you again.

36
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:47,000
The energy, or the Lagrangian of

37
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:53,000
a harmonic oscillator, is x dot squared.

38
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:57,000
And then, for reasons that...

39
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:00,500
If you go back in your notes about

40
00:02:00,500 --> 00:02:04,000
the harmonic oscillators that describe the oscillations of strings,

41
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:07,500
first of all, they had a little

42
00:02:07,500 --> 00:02:11,000
index n, which had to do with...

43
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:13,000
Remember, there were cosines.

44
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:14,000
Cosine n sigma.

45
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:16,000
It was the n of that cosine.

46
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:19,000
How many oscillations...

47
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:22,500
How many oscillations over the interval

48
00:02:22,500 --> 00:02:26,000
from 0 to pi the string makes.

49
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:27,000
So there are...

50
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:29,500
Those x sub n's are the

51
00:02:29,500 --> 00:02:32,000
coordinates describing various kinds of oscillations.

52
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:35,500
That was there, and for reasons

53
00:02:35,500 --> 00:02:39,000
that have no special depth to them,

54
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:42,000
it turned out there was

55
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:45,000
a 4 in the denominator here.

56
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:50,000
That was the kinetic energy, and then the potential energy.

57
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:51,500
If I want to write the

58
00:02:51,500 --> 00:02:53,000
energy, I put a plus sign there.

59
00:02:53,000 --> 00:02:56,000
The potential energy was proportional to x squared.

60
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:58,000
Same thing.

61
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:00,000
x sub n squared.

62
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:02,000
It looks like we've...

63
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:11,000
Somebody didn't do their...

64
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:17,000
It was x sub n squared, divided also by 4.

65
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:19,500
And then, sitting in front, is the

66
00:03:19,500 --> 00:03:22,000
square of the frequency of the oscillator.

67
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:25,000
And that was actually just n squared.

68
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:28,500
That's what we got for the

69
00:03:28,500 --> 00:03:32,000
energy of the nth mode of oscillation.

70
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:34,000
x dot squared.

71
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:36,000
And it's a harmonic oscillator.

72
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:38,000
Kinetic energy plus potential energy.

73
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:39,000
That's the Lagrangian.

74
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:40,000
That's the energy.

75
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:42,000
Call it E.

76
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:49,000
The Lagrangian is x dot n squared.

77
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:53,000
You know, I'm going to stop writing n.

78
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:54,000
But remember.

79
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:56,000
I'm talking about x sub n.

80
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:59,000
There's x dot squared minus

81
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:02,000
n squared x squared over 4.

82
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:04,000
That's Lagrangian.

83
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:07,000
From this, you can work out Lagrange's equations of motion.

84
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:09,500
And you can discover that

85
00:04:09,500 --> 00:04:12,000
the oscillator oscillates with frequency n.

86
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:14,000
Okay?

87
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:17,000
Let's next go to the Hamiltonian.

88
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:18,000
We want to do quantum mechanics.

89
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:20,500
The way to go to quantum

90
00:04:20,500 --> 00:04:23,000
mechanics is to first construct the Hamiltonian.

91
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:25,000
And then do some tricks with it.

92
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:27,000
Let's first construct the Hamiltonian.

93
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:28,000
I'll remind you.

94
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:29,000
Oops.

95
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:30,000
This is over 4.

96
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:31,000
Somebody should have corrected me.

97
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:33,000
You all fail.

98
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:35,000
x dot squared over 4.

99
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:36,000
Okay.

100
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:37,000
So what do you do?

101
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:38,000
The first thing you do.

102
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:41,000
What's the first step in constructing Hamiltonians?

103
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:45,000
The first step is to replace

104
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:49,000
the x dots by the momenta.

105
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:51,000
The momenta p.

106
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:54,000
So if you remember, the derivative of a Lagrangian

107
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:57,000
with respect to the velocity is called the momentum.

108
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:01,500
So in this case, with this particular factor of 4

109
00:05:01,500 --> 00:05:06,000
here, the momentum would be x dot divided by 2.

110
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:07,000
Why?

111
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:08,000
Because when I differentiate with respect

112
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:09,000
to x dot, I get a 2.

113
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:11,000
That cancels a 2 in the

114
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:13,000
denominator and leaves a 2 there.

115
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:15,000
That's the first step.

116
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:19,000
Next step is you rewrite the energy.

117
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:25,000
In terms of instead of x dots, you use p's.

118
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:27,500
So we just have to solve for

119
00:05:27,500 --> 00:05:30,000
x dot and plug it in here.

120
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:32,000
What does that give us?

121
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:34,000
That gives us, let's see, x dot squared

122
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:36,000
will be 4 p squared divided by 4.

123
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:41,000
So this will be p squared with no 4.

124
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:45,000
And then potential energy doesn't change.

125
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:48,000
Plus n squared.

126
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:53,000
And then n squared, x squared over 4.

127
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:59,000
And that we now call the Hamiltonian, H.

128
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:05,000
The quantum mechanical Hamiltonian is exactly the same.

129
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:08,000
Except that it becomes an operator.

130
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:11,000
An operator in the space of states.

131
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:13,000
Okay, now the trick is

132
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:15,000
always the same for harmonic oscillators.

133
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:17,000
Let's just erase all of this.

134
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:21,000
This could have been our starting point right here.

135
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:23,000
You look at this, it's the sum of squares.

136
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:26,000
A squared plus b squared.

137
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:28,000
You write that a squared plus b squared,

138
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:31,000
a squared minus b squared is what?

139
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:33,000
It's a plus b times a minus b.

140
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:38,000
How about a squared plus b squared?

141
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:45,000
That's a plus ib times a minus ib.

142
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:46,000
Work it out.

143
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:48,000
You get an a squared.

144
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:51,000
Minus i times plus i is plus.

145
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:53,000
So you get plus b squared.

146
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:55,000
And the cross term goes away.

147
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:58,000
So you look at this, it's the sum of squares.

148
00:06:58,000 --> 00:06:59,000
And you rewrite it.

149
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:01,000
It's the sum of squares in,

150
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:03,000
what is this term a square of?

151
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:06,000
This term is a square of nx over 2.

152
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:07,000
Right?

153
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:10,500
Alright, so we write that this is

154
00:07:10,500 --> 00:07:14,000
nx over 2 plus ip times nx.

155
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:15,000
Right?

156
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:20,000
nx over 2 minus ip.

157
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:22,000
That's the Hamiltonian.

158
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:23,000
Okay?

159
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:25,000
Next step.

160
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:29,000
You give these two things names, but not quite.

161
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:33,000
First, let's think about the

162
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:37,000
commutation relations between these two.

163
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:39,500
Of course, one of these is essentially

164
00:07:39,500 --> 00:07:42,000
the creation operator or the raising operator.

165
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:45,000
The other one is essentially the lowering operator.

166
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:48,500
But we have to figure out which is which and the

167
00:07:48,500 --> 00:07:52,000
numerical coefficients in order to make them creation and annihilation operators.

168
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:56,000
I'll just put over here for your, to remind you.

169
00:07:56,000 --> 00:08:00,000
The commutation relations between annihilation operators, let's call

170
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:04,000
them a minus and creation operators a plus.

171
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:06,000
A plus when it acts

172
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:08,000
raises the energy by one unit.

173
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:13,000
A minus lowers the energy by one unit.

174
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:16,000
This commutation relation is just one.

175
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:18,500
So that's how we

176
00:08:18,500 --> 00:08:21,000
identify creation and annihilation operators.

177
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:22,500
They're operators which are

178
00:08:22,500 --> 00:08:24,000
complex conjugates of each other.

179
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:27,000
These two are complex conjugates of each other.

180
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:29,000
And their commutation relation is one.

181
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:35,000
So let's work out the commutation relations between these.

182
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:37,000
And just check if we get one.

183
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:39,000
We won't get one.

184
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:40,000
Alright?

185
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:42,000
What's the commutation relation between x and p?

186
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:48,000
Do you remember the commutator between x and p?

187
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:50,000
Anybody remember?

188
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:53,000
I'm setting h bar to one.

189
00:08:53,000 --> 00:08:56,000
What else besides h bar?

190
00:08:56,000 --> 00:08:59,000
I.

191
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:02,000
Go back and try to remember why that's true.

192
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:05,000
xp minus px is i.

193
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:08,000
Alright, now here we have x.

194
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:11,000
We have a commutator of n over 2.

195
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:15,000
A minus i times the commutator of x and p.

196
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:17,000
So let's first...

197
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:19,000
Oh, first of all, what about

198
00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:21,000
the commutator between this and this?

199
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:25,000
That's zero because anything commutes with itself.

200
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:27,000
Likewise, p with p.

201
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:30,000
The only terms are the cross terms

202
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:33,000
x with p and p with x.

203
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:34,000
Alright, so if we just

204
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:35,000
look at the first term here,

205
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:39,000
or the cross term here,

206
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:43,000
that will give us n over 2.

207
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:46,000
It'll give us a minus i from here.

208
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:48,500
But then the commutator of

209
00:09:48,500 --> 00:09:51,000
x with p is plus i.

210
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:54,000
So that gets multiplied by plus i.

211
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:58,000
All together makes it just n over 2.

212
00:09:58,000 --> 00:09:59,000
So far.

213
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:03,000
That's the commutator of this guy with that one.

214
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:05,000
How about this one with this one?

215
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:08,000
Again, I see an n over 2.

216
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:10,000
I see an i.

217
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:11,500
But now I have the p's

218
00:10:11,500 --> 00:10:13,000
and the x's in the opposite order.

219
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:16,000
The result is exactly the same thing.

220
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:18,000
Just double it.

221
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:20,500
So this one and this

222
00:10:20,500 --> 00:10:23,000
one give you the same thing.

223
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:24,000
It just doubles.

224
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:27,000
All of this just gives us n.

225
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:30,000
Now, I wanted to get 1.

226
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:32,000
But I got n.

227
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:34,000
What do I do with it?

228
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:37,000
I just divide both equations,

229
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:41,000
both of these operators by the square root of n.

230
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:43,500
In other words, let's divide each of

231
00:10:43,500 --> 00:10:46,000
these by the square root of n.

232
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:48,000
Likewise over here.

233
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:50,000
1 over the square root of n.

234
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:55,000
And that now eats up this n here.

235
00:10:55,000 --> 00:10:56,500
And that's the way to remember

236
00:10:56,500 --> 00:10:58,000
it if you're on a desert island

237
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:03,000
and you can't remember what combination of x's and p's

238
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:06,000
are creation and annihilation operators.

239
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:09,000
Compared with over here,

240
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:10,000
this is n.

241
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:12,000
This is 1 now.

242
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:14,500
If I had my

243
00:11:14,500 --> 00:11:17,000
creation and annihilation operators interchanged,

244
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:19,000
I would get minus 1.

245
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:25,000
So we then identify the annihilation operator, a minus,

246
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:27,000
is 1 over the square root of n.

247
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:32,000
That means square root of n x over 2

248
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:35,000
plus i over the square root of n p.

249
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:43,000
And the creation operator is the same thing

250
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:45,000
except with a minus sign.

251
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:52,000
I just do that to remind you.

252
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:56,000
There are creation and annihilation operators.

253
00:11:56,000 --> 00:12:00,000
The creation operators increase the energy by 1 unit.

254
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:01,500
And when I say 1

255
00:12:01,500 --> 00:12:03,000
unit, I now mean 1 unit.

256
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:06,000
The frequency of this oscillator is n.

257
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:07,000
Oops.

258
00:12:07,000 --> 00:12:08,000
n units.

259
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:09,000
Little n units.

260
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:10,000
Which n?

261
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:13,000
Well, it depends on which xn I'm talking about.

262
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:16,000
We can now put in, we

263
00:12:16,000 --> 00:12:19,000
can now put back our n's.

264
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:24,000
There's a creation operator and an annihilation operator

265
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:27,000
for each oscillation, for each

266
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:30,000
possible oscillation of the string.

267
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:33,000
And the frequency is n.

268
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:35,000
The frequency of the oscillator is n.

269
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:37,000
The frequency, of course, is

270
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:39,000
the amount of energy that's added

271
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:42,000
by exciting the oscillator once.

272
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:47,000
So we can work out then what the energies are,

273
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:50,000
what the energy spectrum is,

274
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:54,000
and do the quantum mechanics of the oscillators.

275
00:12:54,000 --> 00:12:58,000
And that's basically the spectrum of these strings.

276
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:00,000
Now, we'll come back to it in a minute.

277
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:01,500
