00:25:51,000 --> 00:25:58,000
Spin 2, 5 states, and so forth.

557
00:25:58,000 --> 00:26:02,000
However, massless particles are special.

558
00:26:02,000 --> 00:26:05,000
They don't fall into this category.

559
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:11,000
A massless spin 0 state only has 1 state.

560
00:26:11,000 --> 00:26:13,500
But a massless spin 1

561
00:26:13,500 --> 00:26:16,000
state has 2 states, not 3.

562
00:26:16,000 --> 00:26:18,500
A massless spin 2 state

563
00:26:18,500 --> 00:26:21,000
system has 2 states, not 5.

564
00:26:21,000 --> 00:26:24,000
A massless spin 3, 2 states.

565
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:26,500
The only one which is the exceptional sort

566
00:26:26,500 --> 00:26:29,000
of odd man out is the spin 0.

567
00:26:29,000 --> 00:26:31,000
It has only 1 state.

568
00:26:31,000 --> 00:26:34,000
All others have 2 states.

569
00:26:35,000 --> 00:26:38,000
For massless, for massless.

570
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:40,000
How do we understand that?

571
00:26:40,000 --> 00:26:41,000
How can that be...

572
00:26:41,000 --> 00:26:43,000
The question is how can it be consistent?

573
00:26:43,000 --> 00:26:45,000
How can it be consistent?

574
00:26:45,000 --> 00:26:47,000
I will tell you what the 2 states are.

575
00:26:47,000 --> 00:26:51,500
In every case here, yeah, the particle,

576
00:26:51,500 --> 00:26:56,000
imagine it moving along a certain axis.

577
00:26:56,000 --> 00:26:59,000
For the moment, it could be massless or massive.

578
00:26:59,000 --> 00:27:03,000
And let's suppose it's moving along a certain axis.

579
00:27:03,000 --> 00:27:08,000
Let me consider the component of spin along that axis.

580
00:27:08,000 --> 00:27:10,000
What's the maximum...

581
00:27:10,000 --> 00:27:12,000
Let's forget spin 0 here.

582
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:13,000
That only has 1 state.

583
00:27:13,000 --> 00:27:16,000
But let's go to spin 1.

584
00:27:16,000 --> 00:27:21,000
What's the maximum spin along any given axis?

585
00:27:21,000 --> 00:27:24,000
Well, the answer is the spins along any

586
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:27,000
axis can be 1, 0, and minus 1.

587
00:27:27,000 --> 00:27:30,000
How about for spin 2?

588
00:27:32,000 --> 00:27:37,000
0, minus 1, and minus 2.

589
00:27:37,000 --> 00:27:40,000
In each case, there is always a maximum spin.

590
00:27:40,000 --> 00:27:43,000
In this case, a maximum and a minimum.

591
00:27:43,000 --> 00:27:46,500
Meaning to say, maximum positive and

592
00:27:46,500 --> 00:27:50,000
a minimum which would be negative.

593
00:27:50,000 --> 00:27:53,500
Those can be thought of as the states where

594
00:27:53,500 --> 00:27:57,000
the spin is maximally along the direction of motion

595
00:27:57,000 --> 00:28:01,000
or maximally opposed to the direction of motion.

596
00:28:02,000 --> 00:28:06,500
Now, as far as whether the spin is along

597
00:28:06,500 --> 00:28:11,000
the direction of motion or against the direction of motion,

598
00:28:11,000 --> 00:28:14,000
that's really an arbitrary choice of

599
00:28:14,000 --> 00:28:17,000
right hand versus left hand rule.

600
00:28:17,000 --> 00:28:21,000
Spin has to do with rotation.

601
00:28:21,000 --> 00:28:26,000
Momentum is a vector along an axis.

602
00:28:26,000 --> 00:28:31,000
My right hand, my fingers curl right-handedly.

603
00:28:31,000 --> 00:28:34,000
My left hand, they curl left-handedly.

604
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:41,000
A spin that way is considered positive along the axis.

605
00:28:41,000 --> 00:28:44,000
And a spin that-a-way is

606
00:28:44,000 --> 00:28:47,000
considered negative along the same axis.

607
00:28:47,000 --> 00:28:51,000
Well, simple reflection symmetry tells you if

608
00:28:51,000 --> 00:28:55,000
you have one, you better have the other.

609
00:28:55,000 --> 00:28:57,500
If you have a right hand and

610
00:28:57,500 --> 00:29:00,000
you're in a world with reflection symmetry,

611
00:29:00,000 --> 00:29:02,000
you'll have a left hand.

612
00:29:02,000 --> 00:29:04,000
If there's a right-handed particle that can spin that way,

613
00:29:04,000 --> 00:29:06,000
there'll be a left-handed one

614
00:29:06,000 --> 00:29:08,000
that can spin the other way.

615
00:29:08,000 --> 00:29:12,000
So, if you have a particle moving down

616
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:16,000
the axis with the maximum component of spin,

617
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:20,000
there must be another possibility.

618
00:29:20,000 --> 00:29:23,500
The particle must also be capable of having

619
00:29:23,500 --> 00:29:27,000
the opposite, namely the minimum component of spin.

620
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:28,500
But is there any reason why

621
00:29:28,500 --> 00:29:30,000
it has to have spins in between?

622
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:32,000
So let's take the spin one case.

623
00:29:32,000 --> 00:29:36,000
The spin one case, the three states along

624
00:29:36,000 --> 00:29:40,000
that axis have spin one, zero, and minus one.

625
00:29:40,000 --> 00:29:43,000
Those are the three states.

626
00:29:43,000 --> 00:29:45,500
We see because of reflection invariance that if

627
00:29:45,500 --> 00:29:48,000
it has a spin one along the axis,

628
00:29:48,000 --> 00:29:52,000
it must also have a spin minus one.

629
00:29:52,000 --> 00:29:56,000
Must it also have a spin zero?

630
00:29:56,000 --> 00:30:00,000
Well, the answer-a z component of spin.

631
00:30:00,000 --> 00:30:03,000
A z component of spin along that axis.

632
00:30:03,000 --> 00:30:06,000
And the answer, as I said, depends

633
00:30:06,000 --> 00:30:09,000
on whether the particle is massive or massless.

634
00:30:09,000 --> 00:30:12,000
So let me show you why.

635
00:30:12,000 --> 00:30:15,000
Supposing the particle is massive to begin with.

636
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:18,500
And supposing it has-let me argue that

637
00:30:18,500 --> 00:30:22,000
there must be three states that it has.

638
00:30:22,000 --> 00:30:26,000
If it's moving down the z axis,

639
00:30:26,000 --> 00:30:30,000
and it has spin along the z axis,

640
00:30:30,000 --> 00:30:35,000
so it's rotating this away.

641
00:30:35,000 --> 00:30:38,000
Now imagine bringing that particle to rest.

642
00:30:38,000 --> 00:30:41,000
Or better yet, moving in such a

643
00:30:41,000 --> 00:30:44,000
way that you keep up with the particle.

644
00:30:44,000 --> 00:30:45,500
It's not moving with the speed

645
00:30:45,500 --> 00:30:47,000
of light. It's got a mass.

646
00:30:47,000 --> 00:30:49,000
You keep up with it, and you look

647
00:30:49,000 --> 00:30:51,000
at the particle, and the particle's at rest.

648
00:30:51,000 --> 00:30:53,000
The particle is at rest.

649
00:30:53,000 --> 00:30:59,000
So now you've discovered that there's a particle at rest,

650
00:30:59,000 --> 00:31:05,000
but moving along with it doesn't change its spin.

651
00:31:05,000 --> 00:31:06,500
If it's rotating this way and going down

652
00:31:06,500 --> 00:31:08,000
that axis, and you keep up with it,

653
00:31:08,000 --> 00:31:11,000
it will still be rotating that way.

654
00:31:11,000 --> 00:31:15,000
So it still has spin one along this axis.

655
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:17,000
It has spin one along this axis.

656
00:31:17,000 --> 00:31:20,000
But now that you've brought it to rest,

657
00:31:20,000 --> 00:31:23,000
you can rotate it,

658
00:31:23,000 --> 00:31:27,000
and then boost it back up.

659
00:31:27,000 --> 00:31:29,500
In that case, you've created a

660
00:31:29,500 --> 00:31:32,000
particle which is neither spinning about,

661
00:31:32,000 --> 00:31:36,000
which neither has maximal spin in that direction,

662
00:31:36,000 --> 00:31:38,000
or minimum spin in that direction,

663
00:31:38,000 --> 00:31:42,000
but which now has spin pointing out of the blackboard,

664
00:31:42,000 --> 00:31:45,000
even though the particle is moving down that direction.

665
00:31:45,000 --> 00:31:47,500
And you did that by, first

666
00:31:47,500 --> 00:31:50,000
of all, bringing the particle to rest,

667
00:31:50,000 --> 00:31:52,500
and then saying, if you're living

668
00:31:52,500 --> 00:31:55,000
in a world with rotation invariants,

669
00:31:55,000 --> 00:31:57,000
if there's a particle at rest,

670
00:31:57,000 --> 00:32:00,000
whose spin is pointing along that axis,

671
00:32:00,000 --> 00:32:02,500
it must also be possible to

672
00:32:02,500 --> 00:32:05,000
have it pointing along that axis.

673
00:32:05,000 --> 00:32:08,000
Another way to think about it is,

674
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:11,000
you could imagine after having brought it to rest,

675
00:32:11,000 --> 00:32:14,000
boosting it along the perpendicular axis,

676
00:32:14,000 --> 00:32:16,500
either way, you wind up with

677
00:32:16,500 --> 00:32:19,000
a particle whose spin is perpendicular

678
00:32:19,000 --> 00:32:21,000
to the axis of motion.

679
00:32:21,000 --> 00:32:23,000
And that must be the case, because

680
00:32:23,000 --> 00:32:25,000
you can bring a particle to rest,

681
00:32:25,000 --> 00:32:26,000
and then,

682
00:32:26,000 --> 00:32:29,000
accelerate it in a perpendicular direction,

683
00:32:29,000 --> 00:32:31,000
without changing its spin.

684
00:32:31,000 --> 00:32:34,000
Okay, so, conclusion.

685
00:32:34,000 --> 00:32:39,000
If you have a massive particle,

686
00:32:39,000 --> 00:32:42,000
it must have all three states.

687
00:32:42,000 --> 00:32:45,000
Spin along that axis, spin along that axis,

688
00:32:45,000 --> 00:32:48,000
and that's not enough, you have to be

689
00:32:48,000 --> 00:32:51,000
able to make up spin along the perpendicular axis.

690
00:32:51,000 --> 00:32:54,000
On the other hand, if the particle is massless,

691
00:32:54,000 --> 00:32:55,500
there is nothing you can

692
00:32:55,500 --> 00:32:57,000
do to bring it to rest.

693
00:32:57,000 --> 00:32:59,500
Any Lorentz transformation will leave it

694
00:32:59,500 --> 00:33:02,000
moving with the speed of light.

695
00:33:02,000 --> 00:33:05,000
You cannot bring it to rest, and then,

696
00:33:05,000 --> 00:33:08,000
rotate out from under the spin,

697
00:33:08,000 --> 00:33:12,000
and boost it in another direction.

698
00:33:12,000 --> 00:33:15,000
The implication is,

699
00:33:15,000 --> 00:33:18,000
that if particles have zero mass,

700
00:33:18,000 --> 00:33:20,500
then it's perfectly consistent that

701
00:33:20,500 --> 00:33:23,000
all they have is maximal spin,

702
00:33:23,000 --> 00:33:25,000
and minimal spin,

703
00:33:25,000 --> 00:33:27,000
and nothing in between.

704
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:28,000
That's typically the case.

705
00:33:28,000 --> 00:33:32,000
Now, you know this in another guise for the photon.

706
00:33:32,000 --> 00:33:37,000
What guise is it for the photon?

707
00:33:37,000 --> 00:33:41,000
The polarization of light.

708
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:43,000
The polarization of light can be

709
00:33:43,000 --> 00:33:45,000
described in a number of ways.

710
00:33:45,000 --> 00:33:50,000
It can be described as linear polarization,

711
00:33:50,000 --> 00:33:52,000
circular polarization,

712
00:33:52,000 --> 00:33:56,000
but if you describe it in terms of circular polarization,

713
00:33:56,000 --> 00:34:01,000
circular polarization, incidentally, corresponds to photons,

714
00:34:01,000 --> 00:34:03,000
depending on whether the circular

715
00:34:03,000 --> 00:34:05,000
polarization is right-handed or left-handed,

716
00:34:05,000 --> 00:34:08,000
it corresponds to an assemblage of photons,

717
00:34:08,000 --> 00:34:12,000
which are either right-hand spinning or left-hand spinning.

718
00:34:16,000 --> 00:34:21,000
There are no photons which are not polarized at all.

719
00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:24,000
Polarization is always perpendicular

720
00:34:24,000 --> 00:34:26,000
to the direction of motion.

721
00:34:26,000 --> 00:34:28,000
It's either right-handed or left-handed.

722
00:34:28,000 --> 00:34:30,000
Now, what about linear polarization?

723
00:34:30,000 --> 00:34:32,000
There's linear polarization,

724
00:34:32,000 --> 00:34:33,500
and I'm going to tell

725
00:34:33,500 --> 00:34:35,000
you now what linear polarization is.

726
00:34:35,000 --> 00:34:39,000
Linear polarization, if you have...

727
00:34:39,000 --> 00:34:42,500
Linear polarization is not zero angular

728
00:34:42,500 --> 00:34:46,000
momentum along the direction of motion.

729
00:34:46,000 --> 00:34:50,000
It's a quantum superposition of the two possibilities.

730
00:34:50,000 --> 00:34:52,500
Circular polarization to the right

731
00:34:52,500 --> 00:34:55,000
and circular polarization to the left.

732
00:34:55,000 --> 00:34:58,000
What's the difference between saying it's

733
00:34:58,000 --> 00:35:01,000
a linear superposition of polarization states

734
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:05,000
and saying it has no angular momentum at all?

735
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:08,000
It has equal probability for spinning to

736
00:35:08,000 --> 00:35:11,000
the right and spinning to the left.

737
00:35:11,000 --> 00:35:13,500
So doesn't that mean that it has,

738
00:35:13,500 --> 00:35:16,000
on the average, no spin at all?

739
00:35:16,000 --> 00:35:17,500
Yes, it does mean that on

740
00:35:17,500 --> 00:35:19,000
the average it has no spin.

741
00:35:20,000 --> 00:35:24,000
But if you measure the angular momentum of that photon,

742
00:35:24,000 --> 00:35:28,000
it will either be right-handed or left-handed.

743
00:35:28,000 --> 00:35:31,000
You will never measure a photon which

744
00:35:31,000 --> 00:35:34,000
has no angular momentum along that direction.

745
00:35:34,000 --> 00:35:37,000
So there are only two states of the photon.

746
00:35:37,000 --> 00:35:41,000
And one other point.

747
00:35:41,000 --> 00:35:45,000
Let's go back to linear polarization.

748
00:35:45,000 --> 00:35:49,000
A photon moving down an axis can be polarized.

749
00:35:49,000 --> 00:35:54,000
Here's the plane perpendicular to the motion of the photon.

750
00:35:54,000 --> 00:35:57,000
If you send it through a plane polarizer,

751
00:35:57,000 --> 00:36:01,000
it can be polarized, let's say, along the y-axis,

752
00:36:01,000 --> 00:36:04,000
or it can be polarized along the x-axis.

753
00:36:04,000 --> 00:36:07,000
The polarization is a vector.

754
00:36:07,000 --> 00:36:10,000
But it's a vector which is always perpendicular

755
00:36:10,000 --> 00:36:13,000
to the direction of motion of the photon.

756
00:36:13,000 --> 00:36:16,000
It's always perpendicular, and the words for

757
00:36:16,000 --> 00:36:19,000
that are the polarization is always transverse.

758
00:36:19,000 --> 00:36:23,000
There is no polarization of the photon where the polarization where

759
00:36:23,000 --> 00:36:27,000
the electric field arrow points along the direction of the photon.

760
00:36:27,000 --> 00:36:30,000
That's not allowed by Maxwell's equations.

761
00:36:30,000 --> 00:36:32,000
Maxwell's equations tell you

762
00:36:32,000 --> 00:36:34,000
the electric and magnetic field,

763
00:36:34,000 --> 00:36:36,000
and therefore the polarization of the photon,

764
00:36:36,000 --> 00:36:39,000
are perpendicular to the direction of motion.

765
00:36:39,000 --> 00:36:43,000
So you can have two states of two different polarizations.

766
00:36:43,000 --> 00:36:47,000
You could call it the x-polarization state of the photon,

767
00:36:47,000 --> 00:36:49,000
or you could call it the y-polarization state.

768
00:36:49,000 --> 00:36:56,000
Neither of them is circular polarization.

769
00:36:56,000 --> 00:37:00,000
What about circular polarization?

770
00:37:00,000 --> 00:37:04,000
Circular polarization is a linear superposition,

771
00:37:04,000 --> 00:37:07,000
a quantum mechanical linear superposition,

772
00:37:07,000 --> 00:37:12,000
right-handed, let's call it right-hand polarization,

773
00:37:12,000 --> 00:37:15,000
which means spin right-handed.

774
00:37:15,000 --> 00:37:18,000
That's equal to the state x

775
00:37:18,000 --> 00:37:22,000
plus i times the state y.

776
00:37:30,000 --> 00:37:32,000
No, I won't say it.

777
00:37:34,000 --> 00:37:38,000
Left-handed is x minus iy.

778
00:37:38,000 --> 00:37:40,000
Is it the same like the

779
00:37:40,000 --> 00:37:42,000
silver polarization, like the Stern-Berlus experiment?

780
00:37:42,000 --> 00:37:44,000
If you said i-silver, is

781
00:37:44,000 --> 00:37:46,000
it the same type of explanation?

782
00:37:46,000 --> 00:37:50,000
No, it's just circular polarization.

783
00:37:50,000 --> 00:37:52,000
Just circular polarization.

784
00:37:52,000 --> 00:37:54,000
Just pure circular polarization.

785
00:37:54,000 --> 00:37:58,000
Circular polarization is a quantum linear superposition.

786
00:37:58,000 --> 00:38:02,000
For each photon, a circularly polarized photon

787
00:38:02,000 --> 00:38:07,000
is a quantum superposition of a x-polarized photon

788
00:38:07,000 --> 00:38:09,000
and a y-polarized photon.

789
00:38:09,000 --> 00:38:10,000
Let me ask this.

790
00:38:10,000 --> 00:38:12,000
Supposing I didn't put the i here.

791
00:38:12,000 --> 00:38:14,000
Supposing I just considered x plus y,

792
00:38:14,000 --> 00:38:17,000
what kind of photon would that be?

793
00:38:17,000 --> 00:38:19,000
Linearly polarized.

794
00:38:19,000 --> 00:38:21,000
That would be linearly polarized,

795
00:38:21,000 --> 00:38:25,000
but at a 45-degree angle to the axes.

796
00:38:25,000 --> 00:38:27,500
So, if all you are allowed

797
00:38:27,500 --> 00:38:30,000
to do is put real numbers here,

798
00:38:30,000 --> 00:38:33,000
you would make linear polarization,

799
00:38:33,000 --> 00:38:35,500
which could point in any direction perpendicular

800
00:38:35,500 --> 00:38:38,000
to the direction of motion of the photon.

801
00:38:38,000 --> 00:38:42,000
But having i's available gives you something new.

802
00:38:42,000 --> 00:38:45,000
It gives you circular polarization.

803
00:38:45,000 --> 00:38:49,000
If you use as your basis of states,

804
00:38:49,000 --> 00:38:52,000
the circularly polarized states,

805
00:38:52,000 --> 00:38:55,000
instead of the linearly polarized states,

806
00:38:55,000 --> 00:38:57,000
there are only two of them.

807
00:38:57,000 --> 00:38:59,000
So the angular momentum of the

808
00:38:59,000 --> 00:39:01,000
photon is either along the axis

809
00:39:01,000 --> 00:39:04,000
or along the opposite to the axis.

810
00:39:04,000 --> 00:39:07,000
And there is no photon which

811
00:39:07,000 --> 00:39:10,000
has zero angular momentum along the axis.

812
00:39:12,000 --> 00:39:14,000
The same is true of gravitons.

813
00:39:14,000 --> 00:39:16,000
Slightly differently,

814
00:39:16,000 --> 00:39:20,000
gravitons are spin-2 objects.

815
00:39:20,000 --> 00:39:23,000
If they were massive, they would have five states.

816
00:39:23,000 --> 00:39:26,000
But gravitons only have two states.

817
00:39:26,000 --> 00:39:29,000
They, roughly speaking,

818
00:39:29,000 --> 00:39:30,500
and this is an analogy I

819
00:39:30,500 --> 00:39:32,000
want you to keep in mind.

820
00:39:32,000 --> 00:39:35,000
It's a good analogy, and we'll draw on it.

821
00:39:35,000 --> 00:39:38,000
A graviton moving down the axis

822
00:39:38,000 --> 00:39:42,000
with maximal angular momentum

823
00:39:42,000 --> 00:39:45,000
that means two units of angular momentum

824
00:39:45,000 --> 00:39:47,000
moving along the z-axis

825
00:39:47,000 --> 00:39:54,000
